article.description: Kristen Mann scored 19 points to help the Minnesota Lynx beat the San Antonio Silver Stars 81-55 for a season-ending victory Sunday.
article.headline: Mann dumps in 19 points to help Lynx rout Silver Stars
article.linkText: Mann, Lynx pour it on in win against Silver Stars
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS -- The Minnesota Lynx closed a season of
frustration with something that rarely came around this year -- a
winning streak.

	   Kristen Mann scored 19 points to help the Lynx to an 81-55
victory over the San Antonio Silver Stars in the regular season
finale on Sunday.

	   With the playoffs fast approaching and their seed already locked
up, San Antonio used just six players in the game, and wore down in
the second half as Minnesota cruised.

	   "We wanted to end on a positive note, and tonight was Fan
Appreciation night, so this was for them," Mann said. "The whole
second half was a lot better. Everyone had more energy and the
crowd got into it, so it was fun."

	   Trailing by three at the half, Minnesota went on a 30-10
third-quarter run, opening up a double-digit lead against a San
Antonio lineup of reserves. All five of the Silver Stars' regular
starters spent the game on the bench or in street clothes, while
three Silver Stars got their first starts of the season.

	   "It was obvious they were going to play six players," Lynx
coach Don Zierden said. "At halftime I told them we needed to come
out and make a defensive stand and it would wear them down, and
fortunately it worked out that way."

	   Shanna Crossley had 20 points for San Antonio (20-14), which had
already clinched the second spot in the Western Conference playoffs
and will open the postseason Thursday at Sacramento.

	   Minnesota, which won its final two games after enduring seven-
and 10-game losing streaks earlier in the season, finished a
league-worst 10-24, and has a good chance to land the top pick in
the WNBA draft for the second time in the last three years.

	   Noelle Quinn had 14 assists for the Lynx to set a new franchise
single-game record and grab the team's season mark as well with
148.

	   The Silver Stars emerged from a run-and-gun opening quarter
leading 22-20. The pace slowed considerably in the second quarter,
as the teams combined for just 17 points. San Antonio led 31-28 at
the break thanks to 11 points from Crossley.

	   "We wanted to get some playing time for some players that are
going to be important for us in the playoff," said San Antonio
coach Dan Hughes, who acknowledged fatigue played a role in the
third-quarter turnaround. "We felt really good at halftime. We
came out and we had some difficulty scoring. We'd been able to
tempo the game a little bit with our offense and I thought we lost
that."
